The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, April 01, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, March 31: The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) will announce the annual monetary and credit policy for 2004-05 on May 18, shortly after a new government takes over. RBI governor Y. V. Reddy will unveil the policy at a meeting with the chief executives of major scheduled commercial banks on that day, the central bank said in a release here today. The policy will henceforth be known as the annual policy and not as the monetary and credit policy as it encompasses policies for the entire financial sector and not monetary measures only, a spokesperson said.																								 New Delhi, March 31: The countrys external debts rose 6.5 per cent to a whopping $112.10 billion by the end of 2003, mainly due to a surge in NRI deposits. According to the figures released by the ministry of finance, long-term deposits of non-resident Indians zoomed by 32.5 per cent to $28.96 billion last year pushing up the overall external debt of the country.																								 New Delhi, March 31: The Centres fiscal deficit mounted to Rs 1,10,470 crore till February despite higher growth in tax collections. The fiscal deficit during the 11 months (April-February) amounted to 83.6 per cent of the revised estimate of Rs 1,32,103 crore.																								 Calcutta, March 31: The employees of the Bank of Tokyo Ltds city branch have agreed to a settlement on compensation for termination of service in a bipartite agreement, ending a 20-month stalemate, said lawyers involved in the negotiation.																								 New Delhi, March 31: Japan is providing official development assistance to India worth Rs 5,250 crore to fund eight infrastructure projects.																								 New Delhi, March 31: The Small Industries Development Bank of India (Sidbi) will seek the RBIs permission for offering short-term lending to small companies, chairman V. K. Chopra said.																								 Mumbai, March 31: Air-India (A-I) will take on lease two more Boeing 747-400s to begin the much awaited operations to Los Angeles from mid-June. On Tuesday, the airline board approved the plan.
